{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01NTnq2SfbyKcTxVe84hNAHs","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I understand the vulnerability clearly. The SNI server-name → `SslContext` caches (`sslContextMaps`) in `SslContextProvider` are unbounded `ConcurrentHashMap`s keyed by the TLS SNI server name, which is attacker-controlled during the handshake. A malicious peer sending many distinct server names causes unbounded allocation of `SslContext` objects (native memory) that are never evicted — a memory-exhaustion DoS (CWE-770).\n\nThe remediation: bound these caches with LRU eviction, using a limit propagated from `SslContextManager` (which already carries `cacheMaxSize`, default 256). Caching behavior is preserved; only the retained-entry count is capped.\n\nLet me apply the fix to `SslContextManager` first."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2847,"cache_read_input_tokens":36954,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2847},"output_tokens":5,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"adcdc8d6-c953-4ce7-b545-f3c6c9e0067a","uuid":"f24b04c5-ec88-4cd7-8e01-580a84dae3e2","request_id":"req_011CcdP8ubCLHWYxkQ4vnvHU"}
